"Madsen J., Jaspers C., Tamstorf M., Mortensen C.E., Rigét F.","Long-term effects of grazing and global warming on the composition and carrying capacity of graminoid marshes for moulting geese in east Greenland",2011,"Ambio","40","6",,"638","649",,,10.1007/s13280-011-0170-4,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80052536791&partnerID=40&md5=2d68ae2b9065475fd3b72e9fd6641cd1","Institute of Bioscience, Aarhus University, Frederiksborgvej 399, 4000 Roskilde, Denmark; DTU Aqua, Kavalergaarden 6, 2920 Charlottenlund, Denmark; Ejbyvej 13, 2740 Skovlunde, Denmark","Madsen, J., Institute of Bioscience, Aarhus University, Frederiksborgvej 399, 4000 Roskilde, Denmark; Jaspers, C., DTU Aqua, Kavalergaarden 6, 2920 Charlottenlund, Denmark; Tamstorf, M., Institute of Bioscience, Aarhus University, Frederiksborgvej 399, 4000 Roskilde, Denmark; Mortensen, C.E., Ejbyvej 13, 2740 Skovlunde, Denmark; Rigét, F., Institute of Bioscience, Aarhus University, Frederiksborgvej 399, 4000 Roskilde, Denmark","Greening of the Arctic due to climate warming may provide herbivores with richer food supplies, resulting in higher herbivore densities. In turn, this may cause changes in vegetation composition and ecosystem function. In 19821984, we studied the ecology of non-breeding moulting geese in Jameson Land, low Arctic East Greenland. By then, geese consumed most of the graminoid production in available moss fens, and it appeared that the geese had filled up the available habitat. In 2008, we revisited the area and found that the number of moulting geese and the temperature sum for JuneJuly had tripled, while the above-ground biomass in a moss fen ungrazed by geese had more than doubled. In a goose-grazed fen, the overall plant composition was unchanged, but the frequency of graminoids had decreased and the area with dead vegetation and open spots had increased. We suggest that climate warming has lead to increased productivity, allowing for higher numbers of moulting geese. However, the reduction of vegetation cover by grazing may have longer term negative consequences for the number of geese the habitat can sustain. © Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences 2011.","Barnacle geese; Carex; Climate change; Grazing impact; Herbivory; Pink-footed geese","aboveground biomass; carrying capacity; climate change; ecosystem function; fen; food supply; global warming; grazing pressure; habitat availability; herbivore; herbivory; long-term change; marsh; molt; moss; sedge; vegetation cover; waterfowl; animal; article; biomass; climate; ecosystem; environmental protection; goose; greenhouse effect; Greenland; growth, development and aging; plant; population dynamics; wetland; Animals; Biomass; Climate; Conservation of Natural Resources; Ecosystem; Geese; Global Warming; Greenland; Plants; Population Dynamics; Wetlands; Arctic; Greenland; Jameson Land; Anser; Anser brachyrhynchus; Branta leucopsis; Bryophyta; Carex",,,,,,"Bay, C., Holt, S., (1984) Botanical Studies in Jameson Land (Botaniske Undersøgelser i Jameson Land), 1983, p. 89. , Greenland Fisheries and Environment Research Institute, Report, Copenhagen, Denmark, (in Danish); Bhatt, U.S., Walker, D.A., Raynolds, M.K., Comiso, J.C., Epstein, H.E., Jia, G.S., Gens, R., Pinzon, J.E., Circumpolar Arctic tundra vegetation change is linked to sea ice decline (2010) Earth Interactions, 14, pp. 1-20; Burnham, K.P., Anderson, D.R., (2002) Model Selection and Multimodel Inference: A Practical Information-theoretic Approach, , 2nd ed. New York: Springer; Cadieux, M.C., Gauthier, G., Gagnon, C.A., Bêty, J., Berteaux, D., (2008) Monitoring the Environmental and Ecological Impacts of Climate Change on Bylot Island, Sirmilik National Park, p. 112. , Université Laval, Report, Quebec, Canada; Cappelen, J., (2010) DMI Monthly Climate Data Collection 1768-2009, Denmark, the Faroe Islands and Greenland, p. 52. , Danish Meteorological Institute, Technical Report 10-05 DMI, Copenhagen, Denmark; Forbes, B.C., Fauria, M.M., Zet